==German==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|de|gmh|sameztac|sameztac, samztac}}, from {{inh|de|goh|sambaztag||Sabbath day}}, from {{der|de|got|*𐍃𐌰𐌼𐌱𐌰𐍄𐍉}}, from {{der|de|gkm|σάμβατον||Sabbath}} (compare {{cog|fr|samedi}}, {{cog|fro|sambedi}}, {{cog|rm|somda}}, {{cog|ro|sâmbătă}}, {{cog|hu|szombat}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈzamstʰaːk/|lang=de}} {{a|standard}}
* {{IPA|/ˈzamstʰax/|lang=de}} {{a|northern and central Germany; chiefly colloquial}}
* {{IPA|/ˈsamʃtʰaːk/|lang=de}} {{a|south-western Germany and Switzerland; dialect}}
* {{audio|Samstag.ogg|Samstag|lang=de}}

===Noun===
{{de-noun|m|Samstags|gen2=Samstages|Samstage}}

# {{lb|de|now dominant except in former [[East Germany]]}} [[Saturday]]

====Usage notes====
''Samstag'' is the only common word for “Saturday” in western Germany, southern Germany, Austria, and Switzerland (in standard usage). See {{m|de|Sonnabend}} for information on this (declining) synonym.

